## Sanitization tooling

<!-- PROJECT: This entire section is only relevant if your tool
processes user-supplied data that may contain secrets / PII /
proprietary content.  If your tool processes only synthetic /
public input, delete this section.  Keep the broader pattern:
make it easy for users to submit reproductions safely. -->

The bug-report-surface-area strategy assumes users can sanitise inputs
before submitting.  Without a sanitisation helper, users either submit
raw (security risk for them, leak risk for the project) or skip
submitting (signal loss for the project).  Build the helper as a
release-blocker (MUST tier).

### Architectural decision: integrated, multi-invocation, single source of truth

Build the helper as a **shared library accessible via multiple
invocation paths**, NOT separate implementations.  This avoids the
version-skew + maintenance-fragmentation tax of an ad-hoc script:

1. **`<package>.tools.sanitize` library module** — the actual
   sanitisation logic.  Domain-aware via the existing parsers;
   operates on `<CORE_ABSTRACTION>` rather than raw text.  Single
   source of truth.
2. **CLI subcommand `<package> sanitize`** — for users not running a
   server.
3. **HTTP API endpoint `POST /api/v1/sanitize`** — for users running
   the server (Docker, deployed instance).

A web UI page is **deferred to v0.2.0** contingent on user-feedback
signals showing the friction is real.

### What gets sanitised

Operating on `<CORE_ABSTRACTION>`, the rules are field-typed:

| Field | Replacement |
|---|---|
| `<EXAMPLE: hostnames>` | Counter-per-session: same value → same replacement so cross-references survive |
| `<EXAMPLE: public IPs>` | Documentation ranges (RFC 5737 `192.0.2.x`, `198.51.100.x`, `203.0.113.x`) |
| `<EXAMPLE: secrets / hashes>` | Obvious-fake replacements matching the source format |
| `<...>` | `<...>` |

### `--dry-run` mode (critical for trust)

Print the substitution table before any file gets written.  Framing:
**"Don't trust me; here's exactly what I'll change. Now run it for
real."**  Critical for skeptical audiences.

### Testing surface

For each `<COMPONENT>`, every existing real-fixture round-trips
through sanitisation as a regression-guard.  The same property the
round-trip discipline already enforces extends to the sanitiser.

